<h1>
Expanding the moral circle: New
directions in the moral psychology
of speciesism
</h1>
<br>
<h2>
Chair: Jim Everett, PhD (University of Kent)
</h2>
<br>
<h5>Presentation 1: The emergence of speciesism across development
</h5>

<p>
Authors: Matti Wilks, Lucius Caviola, Guy Kahane, and Paul Bloom <br>
Speaker: Matti Wilks (University of Yale)
</p>
<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
Adults care more about other people than they do about nonhuman
animals. Many of us eat cows and pigs, while few would approve of raising
humans as food. But research is yet to explore the emergence of this bias
across development. We tested children aged 5-9 years (N = 240) and
adults (N = 220) using a forced choice rescue dilemma where subjects had
to choose between, for example, saving one person versus ten dogs or ten
pigs (among other combinations). Results suggest that adults are highly
speciesist, prioritizing humans over large numbers of animals. Children are
more egalitarian, often choosing to save animals. Data from control
conditions (e.g., choosing between saving one person versus ten plates)
suggest that children are understanding the task, and not merely choosing
the largest number. Our findings suggest that speciesism is not a natural
default, but rather emerges over the course of development.
</p>

