<h5>
Presentation 2: Increasing Knowledge about Animals Used as
Food
</h5>

<p>
Authors: Adam Feltz, Silke Feltz, Jacob Caton, Zac Cogley, Mylan Engel,
Ramona Ilea, L. and Syd Johnson <br>
Speaker: Adam Feltz (University of Oklahoma)
</p>

<h5>Abstract
</h5>
<p>
We report two studies concerning the effects of education on animal
consumption behaviors. The first study used an objective measure of
knowledge of animals used as food (Feltz &amp; Feltz, 2019), and
demonstrates that a widely-available, non-optimized educational
infographic can make people more knowledgeable about animals used as
food than those in a control condition (pre-post interaction with infographic
F (1, 193) = 5.06, p = .03, ηp2= .03). In a second study, we present
evidence that those who learn something about the conditions of animals in
an animal ethics class reduce their consumption compared to those who
were not in an animal ethics class or learned nothing about the conditions
of animals (pre-post difference score knowledge by ethics class interaction
F (1, 100) = 6.27, p = .01, ηp2= .06). These results suggest that some
animal education efforts, especially optimized ones, can reduce
consumption of animal products.
</p>

