<h5>
Presentation 3: Moral memory bias about the sentience of animals
</h5>

<p>
Authors: Stefan Leach, Robbie Sutton, Kristof Dhont, Karen Douglas, and
Zara Bergström <br>
Speaker: Stefan Leach (University of Kent)
</p>

<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
The sentience of animals, including their ability to suffer, is central to a
number of important moral issues. It is currently unclear whether people
are, on average, accurate or inaccurate with regards to how they perceive
animals’ sentience, because judgements about animals’ minds have yet to
be investigated in a way that can be compared against objective standards
of accuracy. We present six pre-registered studies (n = 2257), including
one representative sample (n = 1000), testing how people remember
evidence of animals’ sentience; allowing us to objectively determine
whether people overestimate (by remembering more evidence of sentience
vs. insentience) or underestimate (by remembering more evidence of
insentience vs. sentience) animals’ sentience. The results show that meat-
eaters objectively overestimate the sentience of animals that are cared-for
(e.g., dogs) but are largely even-handed about animals that are reared for
food (e.g., pigs). Meat-avoiders, on the other hand, consistently favour
sentience (vs. insentience) for both animals that are cared-for and those
that are reared for food. Finally, memory for sentience (vs. insentience)
selectively fades over time; meaning that people (both meat-eaters and
meat-avoiders) seem to ‘default’ towards seeing animals as more insentient
as time goes on. The results speak to whether people objectively
underestimate or overestimate animal sentience and suggest a possible
mechanism through which people maintain beliefs about animals’
(in)sentience.
</p>

