<h5>Presentation 4: Speciesism, utilitarianism, and guilt
</h5>
<p>Speaker: Jim A.C. Everett (University of Kent)
</p>
<h5>Abstract</h5>
<p>
Increasing amount of work has begun to explore the philosophical concept
of ‘speciesism’ — the assignment of different moral worth based on species
membership — as a psychological construct. Despite views that legitimise
moral distinctions between human and non-human animals being seen all
around the world, much of this work has been done in Western countries.
In this work we validated the Speciesism Scale in a Chinese sample (n =
787) and in both our Chinese sample and a representative US comparison
(n = 956), explored the relationship of speciesism with the endorsement of
utilitarian moral principles, empathic concern, and guilt.
</p>

